<DOC><DOCNO> AP880711-0103 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2227EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MaleProstitution     07-11 0131</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Male Prostitution,0134</SECOND><HEAD>Settlement Reached Over Using Boy In Investigation</HEAD><DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A settlement has been reached in a lawsuitinvolving a juvenile used in an undercover investigation of maleprostitution.   The $12.5 million lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in 1985against the Lexington Urban County Government, alleged that policeused a 14-year-old boy in the 1984 investigation without obtainingconsent from him or his mother.   Attorneys for the American Civil Liberties Union, whorepresented the mother, would not release the amount of the June 27settlement at the request of Lexington officials.   The case had been scheduled for trial later this summer.   Police Chief John McFadden said new guidelines were put in placeon how to deal with similar undercover investigations before thelawsuit was filed.</TEXT></DOC>